In historical texts, the term "Okutsuki" appears in the ''[[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]]'' and "Okutsusutae" (奥津棄戸) in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]''. Initially, it described funerary practices involving the abandonment of corpses<ref>Fujii Masao, ''Basic Knowledge of Buddhist Rites'', Kodansha, 1985, ISBN 4-06-201068-2, p.116.</ref>. Commoners' remains were often left exposed, as evidenced archaeologically in ancient Japan, where there are no burial structures for ordinary people<ref>''[[:en:Azuma Kagami|Azuma Kagami]]'', entry for February 29, 1261 (Kōchō 1): The shogunate forbade corpse abandonment, a practice common even among medieval commoners.</ref>. Terms such as "hafuru" in texts like ''{{ill|Iroha Jirui Shō|ja|伊呂波字類抄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iroha Jirui Shō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 色葉字類抄}}'', ''{{ill|Shinzan-shū|ja|秦山集|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinzan-shū|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}'', and ''[[:en:The Tales of Ise|The Tales of Ise]]'' similarly denote abandonment and share meanings with "Okutsuki". Over time, Shinto-style graves evolved under the influence of later Shinto scholars. During the [[Jōmon period]], disposing of remains in shell mounds served as a ritual to send spirits to the afterlife<ref>Makoto Watanabe, ''Jōmon Period Knowledge: Archaeology Series 4'', Tokyo Bijutsu, ISBN 4-8087-0190-1, 1983, p.132.</ref>.
== Shinto Graves ==
Shinto graves follow structures similar to Buddhist ones but omit incense burning, requiring no [[incense burners]]. Instead, an [[eight-legged stand]] (八足台) is used to offer [[sakaki]] branches.
Gravestones are tall, slender rectangular pillars with pyramid-shaped tops, symbolizing the [[Ame no Murakumo no Tsurugi]], one of the [[Three Sacred Treasures]]. Gravestones are inscribed with "○○ Family Okutsuki" or "○○ Family Okutsushiro." If no gravestone exists, the grave marker is inscribed with "○○ Elder (刀自) Spirit Okutsuki." In Shinto, there are no [[posthumous names]]; instead, the deceased's name is followed by "no Mitama," "no Mikoto," "Reisō," or "Reii."
[[Shrines]] typically do not own cemeteries. To establish a Shinto grave, families must purchase plots in public or private cemeteries.
Military personnel of the [[Empire of Japan]] were often enshrined in Shinto graves separate from their family's ancestral plots. During [[World War II]], sunny locations were allocated for the war dead<ref>Hideyoshi Ukai, ''Temple Disappearance,'' Nikkei BP, ISBN 978-4822279172, p.205.</ref>. Gravestones for officers sometimes included their branch (Army or Navy) and final Rank before their names.
